12_dist_point_to_line


  1. Question

    Find the nearest distance from point \((13,-7)\) to line \(y=-2x-21\).

    For flavor, imagine on a map, a river can be approximated by the line \(y=-2x-21\). You are currently at position \((13,-7)\), and you want to know how far you need to travel to get to the river using the shortest path.


    What is the distance from the point to the line? Your answer should be accurate to within \(\pm 0.01\).


    Solution

    1. The shortest path will be perpendicular to the line (perpendicular to the river).
    2. Since the river’s slope is \(-2\), the path’s slope will be \(\frac{1}{2}\), because perpendicular lines have slopes that are negative reciprocals. In other words, if \(m_1\) and \(m_2\) are slopes of perpendicular lines, then \(m_1\cdot m_2=-1\).
    3. The point-slope form is useful for generating an equation of a line with a specific slope through a specific point. You can think of it as a vertical stretch and shifts of the \(y=x\) function. Anyway, a line through point \((h,k)\) with slope \(m\) can be represented by \(y=m\cdot(x-h)+k\).

    Let function \(r\) represent the river’s line and function \(p\) represent the path’s line. Use point-slope form to represent the path, since we know the path’s slope and a point on the path.

    \[r(x)~=~-2x-21\]

    \[p(x)~=~\frac{1}{2}(x-13)-7\]

    Now, we want to know where the river and path intersect. In other words, we want to find \(x_{\mathrm{i}}\) such that \(r(x_{\mathrm{i}})~=~p(x_{\mathrm{i}})\), where the subscript of \(i\) is used to refer to the intersection.

    \[-2x_{\mathrm{i}}-21~=~\frac{1}{2}(x_{\mathrm{i}}-13)-7\]

    Distribute (to get rid of parentheses).

    \[-2x_{\mathrm{i}}-21~=~\frac{1}{2}x_{\mathrm{i}}+\frac{-13}{2}-7\]

    Now, get rid of denominators by multiplying.

    Multiply both sides by 2 (and distribute to all terms).

    \[{-4}x_{\mathrm{i}}-42~=~x_{\mathrm{i}}-13-14\]

    Combine the two constants on the right side. \[ {-4}x_{\mathrm{i}}-42~=~x_{\mathrm{i}}-27 \] Subtract \(x_{\mathrm{i}}\) from both sides. \[ {-5}x_{\mathrm{i}}-42~=~-27 \] Subtract \(-42\) from both sides. \[ {-5}x_{\mathrm{i}}~=~15 \] Divide both sides by \(-5\). \[ x_{\mathrm{i}}~=~-3 \] We need to find \(y_{\mathrm{i}}\), the vertical coordinate of the intersection. You can find evaluating either \(p(-3)\) or \(r(-3)\).

    \[y_{\mathrm{i}}~=~r(-3)~=~p(-3)\]

    I think it is easier to use function \(r\), which was defined above as \(r(x)=-2x-21\). We will evaluate \(r(-3)\) to get \(y_{\mathrm{i}}\).

    \[y_{\mathrm{i}}~=~ r(-3)\]

    \[y_{\mathrm{i}}~=~ -2(-3)-21\]

    \[y_{\mathrm{i}}~=~ 6-21\]

    \[y_{\mathrm{i}}~=~ -15\]

    So, the river and the path intersect at point \((-3,-15)\). I’ll point out that you can double check this in Desmos by graphing \(y=r(x)\) and \(y=p(x)\).


    Now we can use the distance formula to get our answer. Imagine a right triangle with vertices at the two points and with horizontal and vertical legs. We can find absolute differences of corresponding coordinates to find the legs’ lengths.

    \[|\Delta x| ~=~ |13-(-3)| ~=~ 16\] \[|\Delta y| ~=~ |-7-(-15)| ~=~ 8\]


    So, we can use Pythagorean Theorem to find the distance.

    \[D^2~=~ 16^2+8^2\]

    \[D~=~ \sqrt{16^2+8^2}\]

    \[D~=~ \sqrt{256+64}\]

    \[D~=~ \sqrt{320}\]

    \[D~\approx~ 17.8885438\]



  2. Question

    Find the nearest distance from point \((21,-26)\) to line \(y=3x+1\).

    For flavor, imagine on a map, a river can be approximated by the line \(y=3x+1\). You are currently at position \((21,-26)\), and you want to know how far you need to travel to get to the river using the shortest path.


    What is the distance from the point to the line? Your answer should be accurate to within \(\pm 0.01\).


    Solution

    1. The shortest path will be perpendicular to the line (perpendicular to the river).
    2. Since the river’s slope is \(3\), the path’s slope will be \(\frac{-1}{3}\), because perpendicular lines have slopes that are negative reciprocals. In other words, if \(m_1\) and \(m_2\) are slopes of perpendicular lines, then \(m_1\cdot m_2=-1\).
    3. The point-slope form is useful for generating an equation of a line with a specific slope through a specific point. You can think of it as a vertical stretch and shifts of the \(y=x\) function. Anyway, a line through point \((h,k)\) with slope \(m\) can be represented by \(y=m\cdot(x-h)+k\).

    Let function \(r\) represent the river’s line and function \(p\) represent the path’s line. Use point-slope form to represent the path, since we know the path’s slope and a point on the path.

    \[r(x)~=~3x+1\]

    \[p(x)~=~\frac{-1}{3}(x-21)-26\]

    Now, we want to know where the river and path intersect. In other words, we want to find \(x_{\mathrm{i}}\) such that \(r(x_{\mathrm{i}})~=~p(x_{\mathrm{i}})\), where the subscript of \(i\) is used to refer to the intersection.

    \[3x_{\mathrm{i}}+1~=~\frac{-1}{3}(x_{\mathrm{i}}-21)-26\]

    Distribute (to get rid of parentheses).

    \[3x_{\mathrm{i}}+1~=~\frac{-1}{3}x_{\mathrm{i}}+7-26\]

    Now, get rid of denominators by multiplying.

    Multiply both sides by 3 (and distribute to all terms).

    \[{9}x_{\mathrm{i}}+3~=~-x_{\mathrm{i}}+21-78\]

    Combine the two constants on the right side. \[ {9}x_{\mathrm{i}}+3~=~-x_{\mathrm{i}}-57 \] Subtract \(-x_{\mathrm{i}}\) from both sides. \[ {10}x_{\mathrm{i}}+3~=~-57 \] Subtract \(3\) from both sides. \[ {10}x_{\mathrm{i}}~=~-60 \] Divide both sides by \(10\). \[ x_{\mathrm{i}}~=~-6 \] We need to find \(y_{\mathrm{i}}\), the vertical coordinate of the intersection. You can find evaluating either \(p(-6)\) or \(r(-6)\).

    \[y_{\mathrm{i}}~=~r(-6)~=~p(-6)\]

    I think it is easier to use function \(r\), which was defined above as \(r(x)=3x+1\). We will evaluate \(r(-6)\) to get \(y_{\mathrm{i}}\).

    \[y_{\mathrm{i}}~=~ r(-6)\]

    \[y_{\mathrm{i}}~=~ 3(-6)+1\]

    \[y_{\mathrm{i}}~=~ -18+1\]

    \[y_{\mathrm{i}}~=~ -17\]

    So, the river and the path intersect at point \((-6,-17)\). I’ll point out that you can double check this in Desmos by graphing \(y=r(x)\) and \(y=p(x)\).


    Now we can use the distance formula to get our answer. Imagine a right triangle with vertices at the two points and with horizontal and vertical legs. We can find absolute differences of corresponding coordinates to find the legs’ lengths.

    \[|\Delta x| ~=~ |21-(-6)| ~=~ 27\] \[|\Delta y| ~=~ |-26-(-17)| ~=~ 9\]


    So, we can use Pythagorean Theorem to find the distance.

    \[D^2~=~ 27^2+9^2\]

    \[D~=~ \sqrt{27^2+9^2}\]

    \[D~=~ \sqrt{729+81}\]

    \[D~=~ \sqrt{810}\]

    \[D~\approx~ 28.4604989\]



  3. Question

    Find the nearest distance from point \((19,2)\) to line \(y=\frac{-3}{5}x-7\).

    For flavor, imagine on a map, a river can be approximated by the line \(y=\frac{-3}{5}x-7\). You are currently at position \((19,2)\), and you want to know how far you need to travel to get to the river using the shortest path.

    1. The shortest path will be perpendicular to the line (perpendicular to the river).

    \[r(x)~=~\frac{-3}{5}x-7\]

    \[p(x)~=~\frac{5}{3}(x-19)+2\]

    Now, we want to know where the river and path intersect. In other words, we want to find \(x_{\mathrm{i}}\) such that \(r(x_{\mathrm{i}})~=~p(x_{\mathrm{i}})\), where the subscript of \(i\) is used to refer to the intersection.

    \[\frac{-3}{5}x_{\mathrm{i}}-7~=~\frac{5}{3}(x_{\mathrm{i}}-19)+2\]

    \[\frac{-3}{5}x_{\mathrm{i}}-7~=~\frac{5}{3}x_{\mathrm{i}}+\frac{-95}{3}+2\]

    Now, get rid of denominators by multiplying.

    Multiply both sides by 5 (and distribute to all terms).

    \[{-3}x_{\mathrm{i}}-35~=~{\frac{25}{3}}x_{\mathrm{i}}+\frac{-475}{3}+10\]

    Multiply both sides by 3 (and distribute to all terms).

    \[{-9}x_{\mathrm{i}}-105~=~{25}x_{\mathrm{i}}-475+30\]

    Combine the two constants on the right side. \[ {-9}x_{\mathrm{i}}-105~=~{25}x_{\mathrm{i}}-445 \] Subtract \({25}x_{\mathrm{i}}\) from both sides. \[ {-34}x_{\mathrm{i}}-105~=~-445 \] Subtract \(-105\) from both sides. \[ {-34}x_{\mathrm{i}}~=~-340 \] Divide both sides by \(-34\). \[ x_{\mathrm{i}}~=~10 \] We need to find \(y_{\mathrm{i}}\), the vertical coordinate of the intersection. You can find evaluating either \(p(10)\) or \(r(10)\).

    \[y_{\mathrm{i}}~=~r(10)~=~p(10)\]

    I think it is easier to use function \(r\), which was defined above as \(r(x)=\frac{-3}{5}x-7\). We will evaluate \(r(10)\) to get \(y_{\mathrm{i}}\).

    \[y_{\mathrm{i}}~=~ r(10)\]

    \[y_{\mathrm{i}}~=~ \frac{-3}{5}(10)-7\]

    \[y_{\mathrm{i}}~=~ -6-7\]

    \[y_{\mathrm{i}}~=~ -13\]

    So, the river and the path intersect at point \((10,-13)\). I’ll point out that you can double check this in Desmos by graphing \(y=r(x)\) and \(y=p(x)\).


    Now we can use the distance formula to get our answer. Imagine a right triangle with vertices at the two points and with horizontal and vertical legs. We can find absolute differences of corresponding coordinates to find the legs’ lengths.

    \[|\Delta x| ~=~ |19-10| ~=~ 9\] \[|\Delta y| ~=~ |2-(-13)| ~=~ 15\]


    So, we can use Pythagorean Theorem to find the distance.

    \[D^2~=~ 9^2+15^2\]

    \[D~=~ \sqrt{9^2+15^2}\]

    \[D~=~ \sqrt{81+225}\]

  7. Question

    \[D~\approx~ 30\]



  8. Question

    Find the nearest distance from point \((-19,20)\) to line \(y=\frac{3}{2}x-23\).

    For flavor, imagine on a map, a river can be approximated by the line \(y=\frac{3}{2}x-23\). You are currently at position \((-19,20)\), and you want to know how far you need to travel to get to the river using the shortest path.


    What is the distance from the point to the line? Your answer should be accurate to within \(\pm 0.01\).


    Solution

    1. The shortest path will be perpendicular to the line (perpendicular to the river).
    2. Since the river’s slope is \(\frac{3}{2}\), the path’s slope will be \(\frac{-2}{3}\), because perpendicular lines have slopes that are negative reciprocals. In other words, if \(m_1\) and \(m_2\) are slopes of perpendicular lines, then \(m_1\cdot m_2=-1\).
    3. The point-slope form is useful for generating an equation of a line with a specific slope through a specific point. You can think of it as a vertical stretch and shifts of the \(y=x\) function. Anyway, a line through point \((h,k)\) with slope \(m\) can be represented by \(y=m\cdot(x-h)+k\).

    Let function \(r\) represent the river’s line and function \(p\) represent the path’s line. Use point-slope form to represent the path, since we know the path’s slope and a point on the path.

    \[r(x)~=~\frac{3}{2}x-23\]

    \[p(x)~=~\frac{-2}{3}(x+19)+20\]

    Now, we want to know where the river and path intersect. In other words, we want to find \(x_{\mathrm{i}}\) such that \(r(x_{\mathrm{i}})~=~p(x_{\mathrm{i}})\), where the subscript of \(i\) is used to refer to the intersection.

    \[\frac{3}{2}x_{\mathrm{i}}-23~=~\frac{-2}{3}(x_{\mathrm{i}}+19)+20\]

    Distribute (to get rid of parentheses).

    \[\frac{3}{2}x_{\mathrm{i}}-23~=~\frac{-2}{3}x_{\mathrm{i}}+\frac{-38}{3}+20\]

    Now, get rid of denominators by multiplying.

    Multiply both sides by 2 (and distribute to all terms).

    \[{3}x_{\mathrm{i}}-46~=~{\frac{-4}{3}}x_{\mathrm{i}}+\frac{-76}{3}+40\]

    Multiply both sides by 3 (and distribute to all terms).

    \[{9}x_{\mathrm{i}}-138~=~{-4}x_{\mathrm{i}}-76+120\]

    Combine the two constants on the right side. \[ {9}x_{\mathrm{i}}-138~=~{-4}x_{\mathrm{i}}+44 \] Subtract \({-4}x_{\mathrm{i}}\) from both sides. \[ {13}x_{\mathrm{i}}-138~=~44 \] Subtract \(-138\) from both sides. \[ {13}x_{\mathrm{i}}~=~182 \] Divide both sides by \(13\). \[ x_{\mathrm{i}}~=~14 \] We need to find \(y_{\mathrm{i}}\), the vertical coordinate of the intersection. You can find evaluating either \(p(14)\) or \(r(14)\).

    \[y_{\mathrm{i}}~=~r(14)~=~p(14)\]

    I think it is easier to use function \(r\), which was defined above as \(r(x)=\frac{3}{2}x-23\). We will evaluate \(r(14)\) to get \(y_{\mathrm{i}}\).

    \[y_{\mathrm{i}}~=~ r(14)\]

    \[y_{\mathrm{i}}~=~ \frac{3}{2}(14)-23\]

    \[y_{\mathrm{i}}~=~ 21-23\]

    \[y_{\mathrm{i}}~=~ -2\]

    So, the river and the path intersect at point \((14,-2)\). I’ll point out that you can double check this in Desmos by graphing \(y=r(x)\) and \(y=p(x)\).


    Now we can use the distance formula to get our answer. Imagine a right triangle with vertices at the two points and with horizontal and vertical legs. We can find absolute differences of corresponding coordinates to find the legs’ lengths.

    \[|\Delta x| ~=~ |14-(-19)| ~=~ 33\] \[|\Delta y| ~=~ |-2-(20)| ~=~ 22\]


    So, we can use Pythagorean Theorem to find the distance.

    \[D^2~=~ 33^2+22^2\]

    \[D~=~ \sqrt{33^2+22^2}\]

    \[D~=~ \sqrt{1089+484}\]

    \[D~=~ \sqrt{1573}\]

    \[D~\approx~ 39.661064\]
